explanation.foundational_knowledge:
Before solving angular acceleration problems, identify:

• the initial angular velocity (ω₀);
• the final angular velocity (ω);
• the time taken (t);
• whether the object is speeding up or slowing down.

Since the propeller is rotating faster at the end of the motion, the angular acceleration is positive.

Newton's Second Law states that every acceleration must be produced by a force. In circular motion, the acceleration is directed towards the centre of the circle and is called centripetal acceleration.

The centripetal force depends on three important quantities:

• the mass of the object;
• its speed;
• the radius of the circular path.

A heavier object or a faster-moving object requires a greater centripetal force, while a larger turning radius reduces the required force.

explanation.exam_tip:
For JAMB questions on centripetal force, always:

• write down the known quantities;
• use SI units;
• square the speed before multiplying;
• divide by the radius only after completing the multiplication.

These steps help minimise calculation errors.

explanation.foundational_knowledge:
Before attempting centripetal force calculations, always identify:

• the mass of the object;
• the speed of the object;
• the radius of the circular path; and
• the quantity to be determined.

Remember that increasing the speed greatly increases the required centripetal force because the speed is squared in the formula.

To solve problems involving centripetal force, first identify:

• the mass of the object;
• its speed;
• the radius of the circular path; and
• the quantity to be determined.

The motion is uniform because the speed remains constant.

In circular motion, always identify:

• the mass of the object;
• the speed of the object;
• the radius of the circular path; and
• the quantity to be calculated.

When these quantities are known, the centripetal force can be calculated directly.

Before solving this question, you should understand that circular motion requires an inward force directed towards the centre of the circle. Without this force, the clay would move in a straight line tangent to the circular path because of inertia.

The required centripetal force depends on three quantities:

• the mass of the object;
• its linear speed;
• the radius of the circular path.

Before solving this question, identify:

• the mass of the moving object;
• the speed of the object;
• the radius of the circular path; and
• the quantity to be calculated.

The larger the mass or the greater the speed, the larger the centripetal force required. Conversely, increasing the radius reduces the required centripetal force.

The magnitude of the apparent centrifugal force depends on three factors:

• the mass of the object;
• the speed of rotation;
• the radius of the circular path.

If only the speed changes while the mass and radius remain constant, the change in the apparent centrifugal force is determined entirely by the speed.
